    <h2>Section A: Attempt any TWO question.</h2><h3>Question 1</h3>
<div><p><p>Distinguish rigid and non rigid body. Derive an experssion for rotational kinetic energy and discuss the condition for conservation of energy. A wheel of radius 0.4 m and moment of inertia 1.2 kg-m<sup>2 </sup> pivoted at rthe center, is free to rotate without friction. A rope is wound around it and a 2-kg weight is attached to the rope. When the weight has descended 1.5 m from its starting position, find the rotational velocity of the wheel.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><strong>Difference :</strong></p>
<p>The main difference between ridid bodies and non rigid bodies is that, rigid bodies maintain their shape and size when subjected to external forces, while non-rigid bodies undergo deformation in response to applied forces.</p>
<div class="table_wrapper" style="overflow-x:auto;"><table style="border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%;">
<tbody>
<tr style="height: 24px;">
<td style="width: 14.8797%; height: 24px;"><strong>Basis </strong></td>
<td style="width: 44.9828%; height: 24px;"><strong>Rigid body</strong></td>
<td style="width: 40.4467%; height: 24px;"><strong>Non rigid body</strong></td>
</tr>
<tr style="height: 24px;">
<td style="width: 14.8797%; height: 24px;"><strong>Defination </strong></td>
<td style="width: 44.9828%; height: 24px;">Those bodies that maintain their shape and size under applied force or they deforms  negligibly as compared to the motion that it experiences are rigid bodies.</td>
<td style="width: 40.4467%; height: 24px;">Non rigid bodies are those bodies that changes their shape and size under applied force or they deforms as compared to the motion that it experiences.</td>
</tr>
<tr style="height: 24px;">
<td style="width: 14.8797%; height: 24px;"><strong>Effect of force applied</strong></td>
<td style="width: 44.9828%; height: 24px;">Any force applied to them results only in translational or rotational motion.</td>
<td style="width: 40.4467%; height: 24px;">Any force applied to them results in deformation in elastic i.e reversible  or plastic i.e non reversible in nature</td>
</tr>
<tr style="height: 24px;">
<td style="width: 14.8797%; height: 24px;"><strong>Stress </strong></td>
<td style="width: 44.9828%; height: 24px;">No any internal stress is experienced as there is no any derformation.</td>
<td style="width: 40.4467%; height: 24px;">Internal stress is experienced as there is derformation in the size and shape.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="width: 14.8797%;"><strong>Example</strong></td>
<td style="width: 44.9828%;">Concrete blocks , metal rods, wooden planks etc.</td>
<td style="width: 40.4467%;">Rubber balls, Baloon filled with air, clay etc</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p style="padding-left: 40px;"><strong>Derivation part:</strong></p>
<p>In linear motion, the work done dW by a force F in moving an object through displacement dx is given by:</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">dW = Fdx</p>
<p>similarly in rotational motion F is replaced by τ and dx is replaced by dθ . so,</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">dW = τdθ</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">dW = I dω ⁄dt  dθ &#8212;&#8211; 1</p>
<p>we know that angular velocity is defined as the rate of change of angular displacement</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">ω = dθ ⁄dt</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">dθ = ω dt&#8212;&#8211;2</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>from equation 1 and 2 we can write that ,</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">dW = I ·dω ⁄dt ω· dt</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">dW = I ω dω</p>
<p>on integrating both side we get,</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">∫dW = ∫ I ω dω</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">W = <sup>ω1</sup>∫<sub>ω2 </sub>  I ω dω</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">W = ½ [I ω<sup>2</sup> ]<sub>ω1</sub><sup>ω2</sup></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">W = ½ [Iω<sub>2</sub><sup>2</sup>  &#8211; Iω<sub>1</sub><sup>2</sup> ]</p>
<p>The equation obtained above is similar to ½ mv<sup>2 </sup>as m is represented be I and v by ω above. Hence, the rotational kinetic energy can be given as :</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">W = ½ Iω<sup>2</sup></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>The conservation of energy principle states that energy cannot be created or destroyed, only transformed from one form to another. In the context of rotational kinetic energy, conservation of energy occurs under the conditions:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li>There are no external torque on the system.</li>
<li>There are no external work done on the system.</li>
</ol>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Numerical part:</strong></p>
<p>given ,</p>
<p>radius (r) =0.4 m</p>
<p>moment of inertia (I) = 1.2 kg-m<sup>2</sup></p>
<p>mass (m) = 2 kg</p>
<p>height (h) = 1.5 m</p>
<p>Rotational velocity (ω) = ?</p>
<p>now,<img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-33407 alignright" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/fig.jpg?resize=193%2C351&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="193" height="351"></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>From conservation of energy we know that, potential energy of the body is equal to the sum of the rotational kinetic energy and kinetic energy of the body. so,</p>
<p>for the given weight,</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">P.E = K.E + Rotational K.E</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">mgh = ½mv<sup>2 </sup>+ ½ Iω<sup>2</sup></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">2mgh = mv<sup>2 </sup>+  Iω<sup>2</sup></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">2mgh = mv<sup>2 </sup>+  I · v<sup>2</sup>⁄ r<sup>2</sup></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">2mgh = v<sup>2 </sup>(m + I ⁄ r<sup>2</sup>)</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">v<sup>2 </sup>= 2mgh ⁄ (m + I ⁄ r<sup>2</sup>)</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">v = √2mgh ⁄ (m + I ⁄ r<sup>2</sup>)</p>
<p>placing respective values we get,</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">v = √2· 2· 9.8 · 1.5  ⁄ (2+ 1.2 ⁄ 0.4<sup>2</sup>)</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">v = 2.5 m/s</p>
<p>As we calculated the velocity of wheel as 2.5 m/s we can now calculate the rotational velocity as :</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">v = rω</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">ω = v ⁄ r</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">ω = 2.5 ⁄ 0.4</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">ω = 6.25 rad/sec</p>
<p>Hence, the required rotational velocity is 6.25 rad/sec.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 2</h3>
<div><p><p>Setup Schrodinger equation for Hydrogen atom using spherical polar coordinate. Separate radial and angular part of this equation using appropriate seperation constant. Discuss the separation constant and hence the quantum numbers associated with these two equations.What information can be drawn from the angular part of Schrodinger equation ? Explain .</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>As we know, the hydrogen atom is a system of two particle i.e a proton and a single electron bounded by electrostatic force of attraction.</p>
<p>The potential energy of the electron in the electric field of nucleus is given by:</p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone wp-image-33769 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/New-Doc-04-19-2024-14.36_1.jpg?resize=298%2C151&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="298" height="151"></p>
<p>The electron is represented by the wave function or system bounded by the potential well of columb field so the time independent Schrodinger wave equation is given by :</p>
<p>$$ ∇^{{2}}ψ = \frac{{2m}}{{h^2}}(E -V(r))ψ  = 0 &#8212;2 $$</p>
<p>Where,</p>
<p>$$ ∇^{{2}} = \frac{{∂}}{{∂x^{{2}}}} + \frac{{∂}}{{∂y^{{2}}}} + \frac{{∂}}{{∂z^{{2}}}}$$</p>
<p>is laplacian of ψ (x,y,z).</p>
<p>As the gemotrical symmetry of the problem suggest that it is more convinent to use the spherical polar coordinate syayem i.e r, θ, φ.</p>
<p>The rectangular coordinate are related to the spherical polar coordinate as</p>
<p>$$ x = r sinθ cosφ $$</p>
<p>$$ y = r sinθ sinφ $$</p>
<p>$$ z = r cosθ $$</p>
<p>Now,</p>
<p>The Schrodinger equation in the equation spherical polar coorinate system can be written from eq 1 and 2</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-33770" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/New-Doc-04-19-2024-14.38_1.jpg?resize=2024%2C416&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="2024" height="416"></p>
<p>In the equation the wave function ψ  is a function of r, θ and φ i.e ψ(r, θ, φ). Now, for further calculation the equation in polar coordinate can be easily seprated into three equation each involving a single variable.</p>
<p>$$ ψ(r, θ, φ) = R(r) Φ(φ) Θ(θ) $$</p>
<p>Where,</p>
<p>R(r) is the function of r alone.</p>
<p>Φ(φ) is the function of φ alone.</p>
<p>Θ(θ) is the function of θ alone.</p>
<p>Substuting this value in equation 3 we get,</p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-33771" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/New-Doc-04-19-2024-14.39_1.jpg?resize=2436%2C452&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="2436" height="452"></p>
<p>In the given above equation only ordinary defination is used because each variable depends on only one variable.</p>
<p>$$ Multiplying   eq   4   with   \frac {{r^{{2}}sin^{{2}}θ}}{{RΦΘ}}   we   get, $$</p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-33772" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/New-Doc-04-19-2024-14.39-1_1.jpg?resize=2388%2C848&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="2388" height="848"></p>
<p>The LHS of the above equation is a function of r and θ where RHS is a function of Φ alone. Their equality implies that each side must be a equal constant called magnetic orbital.</p>
<p>quantum no i.e m<sub>l</sub><sup>2 </sup></p>
<p>The RHS of the equation is an ordinary differenciation for Φ. So, this gives the azimuthal equation as</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone wp-image-33773" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/New-Doc-04-19-2024-14.40_1.jpg?resize=262%2C135&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="262" height="135"></p>
<p>If we substitute the value of m<sub>l</sub><sup>2  </sup>for LHS in equation equation 5 and divide the whole equation by sin<sup>2</sup>θ and rearranging the equation we get,</p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-33774" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/New-Doc-04-19-2024-14.41_1-scaled.jpg?resize=2560%2C417&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="2560" height="417"></p>
<p>Again, in this equation different variables appear on each side requiring the both side to be equal to same constant i.e l(l+1).</p>
<p>This equation is called polar equtaion and one on LHS is called radial equation.</p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone wp-image-33775 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/New-Doc-04-19-2024-14.42_1.jpg?resize=376%2C83&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="376" height="83"></p>
<p>The Schrodinger wave equation for hydrogen atom has now been seperated into three equation and their solution is well known in mathematics.</p>
<p>From this we can conclude that</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li>When the azimuthal equation is solved for Φ then the solution is   Φ(φ) = A<sup>im<sub>l</sub>φ    </sup>where <span style="font-size: 13.3333px;"><span style="font-size: 12pt;">m<sub>l</sub> = &#8230;..-3,-2,-1,0,1,2,3&#8230;..   and</span> <span style="font-size: 12pt;">m<sub>l </sub>is magnetic quantum number.</span></span></li>
<li>When we solve the polar equation the solution for the Θ that are finite everywhere for which l = 0,1,2,3&#8230;.</li>
<li>When we solve the radial equation the solution for R remains finite for the value</li>
</ol>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone wp-image-33776" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/New-Doc-04-19-2024-14.42-1_1.jpg?resize=222%2C69&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="222" height="69"></p>
<p>This equation is the same equation as that of the bohr&#8217;s theory we have arrived at a system of three quantum number for simple model of hydrogen which are releted to different quantumn like total quantum no, orbital quantum no etc.</p>
