<h3>Question 3</h3>
<div><p><p>What are RTL and TTL  gates. How memory and clock circuits can be made by using these gates? Show it. Explain the working scheme. Is it true that the TTL logic gates are typically fabricated onto a single integrated circuit(IC).</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><b>Register Transistor Logic(RTL):</b></p>
<p>RTL is a class of digital circuits built using resistors as the input network and bipolar junction transistors (BJTs) as switching devices.</p>
<p class="has-text-align-justify">The RTL circuit consists of resistors at inputs and transistors at the output side. Transistors are used as the switching device. The emitter of the transistor is connected to the ground. The collector terminals are tied together and given to the supply through the resistor R<sub>C</sub>. The collector resistor is known as a passive pull-up resistor.</p>
<p><b>Transistor Transistor Logic(TTL):</b></p>
<p>Transistor-transistor logic (TTL) is a digital logic design in which bipolar transistor s act on direct-current pulses. Many TTL logic gate s are typically fabricated onto a single integrated circuit (IC). TTL ICs usually have four-digit numbers beginning with 74 or 54.</p>
<p class="q-text qu-display--block qu-wordBreak--break-word qu-textAlign--start">There are two types of RTL logic now, one is antique, Resistor Transistor Logic, the other is widely used now for design, Register Transfer Level.</p>
<p class="q-text qu-display--block qu-wordBreak--break-word qu-textAlign--start">The old RTL used a combination of resistors and bipolar transistors to construct inverters, OR, NOR and other basic logic gates. Register Transfer Level is used to take code and transfer it into hardware logic. A single line of RTL script can result in hundreds of logic components.</p>
<p class="q-text qu-display--block qu-wordBreak--break-word qu-textAlign--start">TTL is Transistor Transistor Logic, similar to RTL but replacing most of the resistors with transistors.</p>
<p class="q-text qu-display--block qu-wordBreak--break-word qu-textAlign--start">TTL is the more modern logic family and was used until about the 1990s when everything converted to CMOS (Complementary Metal Oxide Semiconductor ) logic. CMOS has the advantage of much lower current and more robust noise rejection than TTL.</p>
<p class="q-text qu-display--block qu-wordBreak--break-word qu-textAlign--start">All of these families are used to make digital circuits. Any logic function can be implemented with a single type of gate, such as a NOR or NAND gate.</p>
<p class="q-text qu-display--block qu-wordBreak--break-word qu-textAlign--start">A group of four or more NOR gates can make a flip-flop, or simple memory. A series of flip-flops can take the 60Hz line frequency, divide by 60 and make a clock which increments every second. A series of more dividers make the minute and hour indicators.</p>
<p>Yes, it&#8217;s  true that the TTL(Transistor &#8211; Transistor  Logic)  gates are typically fabricated onto a single integrated circuit(IC). This fabrication in single IC (Intrigated Circuit) done typically to reduce the room of complexity in IC and make it more reliable and cost effective.</p>
</div>
<h2>Section B: Attempt any EIGHT question.</h2><h3>Question 4</h3>
<div><p><p>Describe classical free electron model.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>The classical electron free model is a theoritical model which was introduced by P. Drude in 1900 and developed by Lorentz in 1909. The main motive of this model was to explain the electrical conduction in metals or conductors. This model prefers some assumptions for describing the behaviour of the electrons in metal or conductors and they are as follow :</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li>The valance electron contained in an atom are free to move in the spaces from one place to another between the ions within the metallic specimens. These electrons also participate in electrical conduction , so they are also reffered as conduction electrons.</li>
<li>These free electrons behave like gas molecules in a container obeying the laws of kinetic theory of gases.</li>
<li>Free electrons obeys the Maxwell-Boltzmann distribution of velocities. In abscence of of electric field whole e<sup>&#8211; </sup> move with their random thermal velocity as ½ mv<sup>2</sup> = ³⁄2 kT. where , v<sup>2</sup> is the average of thermal speed ,T is the temperature and k is boltzmann conatant</li>
<li>There is no interaction between the conduction electrons.</li>
<li>The mutual repulsion between the negatively charged electron is neglected and the free electron moves with constant potential field making the potential energy of  the electrons constant.</li>
<li>When an electric field is applied to a metal, free electrons are accelerated in the direction opposite to the direction of applied electric field with a velocity called drift velocity represented as v<sub>d </sub>.</li>
</ol>
<p>Despite many simplified assumptions this classical free electron model was able to explain manyproperties of metal like ohm&#8217;s law , emperical formula relating the electrical and thermal conductivities in metal.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 5</h3>
<div><p><p>How electric and magnetif fields are incorporated in electromagnetic wave? Explain.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Electric field is the region which is created when there is attraction and repulsion of electrical charges in the surrounding so, electric field is considered as the invisible force field surrounded by the charges upto which its effect can be observed.</p>
<p>Magnetic field can be considered as the region around the magnet where we can experience the attraction and repulsion i.e the effect of magnetism. Magnetic field can be experienced by the flow of electric charges or due to the change in the electric field.</p>
<p>As described by the Maxwell&#8217;s equation , when there is change in the electric field magnetic field is produced and similarly when there is change in the magnetic field we experience the electric field. Continuing the process of creation of electric and magnetic field simultaneously in perpendicular manner lead to the formation of a wave and this wave is called electromagnetic wave.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-33444" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/electromagnetic-waves.drawio.png?resize=760%2C306&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="760" height="306"></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Electromagnetic waves are created as a outcome of vibrations between an electric and a magnetic field. These fields oscillate in phase and are always perpendiculat to each other. The contineous energy transmission between these fields promote wave propagation.</p>
<p>Hence, we can conclude or determine that the electric field and magnetic field incorporate the electromagnetic wave.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
