<h3>Question 6</h3>
<div><p><p>Describe the following process of IC production: (a) Oxidation and (b) Doping. Explain photolithography in brief.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>An integrated circuit (IC) is an assembly of electronic components in which hundreds to millions of transistors, resistors, and capacitors are interconnected and built up on a thin substrate of semiconductor material (usually silicon) to form a small chip or wafer.</p>
<p>As per the questions we need to deal with the following:</p>
<p><strong>a. Oxidation :</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-33460" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/oxidation.drawio.png?resize=581%2C111&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="581" height="111"></p>
<p>This is the process of adding the oxygen to the silicon (Si) of the wafers in order to convert it to silicon dioxide (SiO<sub>2</sub>). This is done by heating the wafer to the high temperature of about 1000°c to 1200°c in presence of oxygen or vapor. This process introduce the layer of silicon dioxide (SiO2) which protect the silicon wafer from the impurities. Oxidation is done by two ways either dry oxidation or wet oxidation.</p>
<p>When the silicon of the wafers are reacted with the vapour to get the layer of silicon dioxide (SiO2) then this is considered as wet oxidation.</p>
<p>Similarly when the silicon of the wafers are reacted with the oxygen leading to the formation of layer of silicon dioxide (SiO2) then this is considered as dry oxidation.</p>
<p><strong>b.Doping :</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone wp-image-33463" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/dopping.png?resize=416%2C192&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="416" height="192"></p>
<p>The formation of circuit components in chip i.e integrated circuit (IC) is acomplished by introducing the donor and acceptor impurities to the fabricated semiconductor i.e silicon wafer to create localized n-type and p-type regions is renowned as doping. The impurity atoms used for this as donor or acceptor are known as dopant. Dopants can be either trivalent or pentavalent. Two most common ways to acieve doping are diffusion and ion implantation.</p>
<p>This technique can vary the number of electrons and holes in semiconductors leading to increase the electrical conductivity of the semiconductor so that it can be further be utilized as replacement in the integrated circuit (IC).</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>photolithography :</strong></p>
<p>Photolithography is a technique to get some pattern on the smooth surface of the silicon wafer by exposure of it to the UV rays. Through the use of photolithography, complicated patterns may be transferred onto semiconductor substrates in a precise and controlled manner. This is acomplished by exposing parts of wafer to UV rays or light while other parts are protected. This process can be determined by some steps:</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone wp-image-33464" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/photoresist.drawio.png?resize=217%2C223&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="217" height="223"></p>
<ol style="list-style-type: lower-roman;">
<li>Developing a photoresist flim on silicon wafer.</li>
<li>Exposure of the silicon wafer with phoresist to the UV ray.</li>
<li>Removing the selected photoresist as requirement.</li>
<li>This patterned substrate is treated with HF to form a window in the SiO<sub>2 </sub>layer.</li>
<li>Finally the substrate is ready to be dopped after washing the photoresist.</li>
</ol>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>The diagram above shows the photolithography explained by the steps above.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
