<div><p><p>An oscillating block of mass 250 g takes 0.2 sec to move between the endpoints of the motion, which are 50 cm apart. Find the frequency and amplitude of the motion. what is the force constant of the spring?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-60741" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/CamScanner-08-05-2025-12.11_1-scaled.jpg?resize=1645%2C2560&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="1645" height="2560"></p>
</div>
<h3>Question 8</h3>
<div><p><div class="qnbank_number">A potential difference of 100 V is established between the two plates one being the high potential plate. An alpha particle of charge q = 3.2 × 10<sup>-19</sup> C is released from one plate to another plate. What will be the velocity of the alpha particle when it reaches plate? The mass of the proton is 6.70-x 10<sup>-19</sup> kg.</div</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Given,</p>
<p>Potential difference (V) = 100V</p>
<p>Charge of alpha particle (q) = 3.2 × 10<sup>-19</sup> C</p>
<p>Mass of alpha particle (m) = 6.70×10<sup>-19</sup> kg</p>
<p>velocity of alpha particle (ν) = ?</p>
<p>now,</p>
<p>we know that,</p>
<p>$$ \frac{{1}}{{2}} m ν^2 = qV$$</p>
<p>$$ or, ν^2 = \frac {{2qV}}{{m}}$$</p>
<p>$$ or, ν^2 = \frac {{2×3.2 × 10^{{-19}}×100}}{{6.70-x 10^{{-19}}}}$$</p>
<p>$$ or, ν^2 = \frac {{6.4×10^{{-17}}}}{{6.70×10^{{-19}} }}$$</p>
<p>$$ ν = 90.522$$</p>
<p>Hence, the velocity of the alpha particle is 90.522 m/s.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 9</h3>
<div><p><p>Calculate uncertainty in the momentum of electron if uncertainty in its position is 1Å  (10<sup>-10</sup>).</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Given,</p>
<p>Uncertainty in position (Δx) = 1Å  (10<sup>-10</sup>)</p>
<p>Uncertainty in momentum of electron (Δp) = ?</p>
<p>we know that,</p>
<p>plank&#8217;s constant (h) = 6.626×10<sup>-34</sup></p>
<p>from Heisenberg&#8217;s Principle we have,</p>
<p>$$ Δx Δp ≥ \frac{{h}}{{2π}}$$</p>
<p>$$ Δp = \frac{{h}}{{2π}} ×\frac{{1}}{{ Δx}}$$</p>
<p>$$ Δp = \frac{{6.626×10^{{-34}}}}{{2×3.14}} ×\frac{{1}}{{10^{{-10}}}}$$</p>
<p>$$ Δp = 5.28×10^{{-25}} kg m/ sec $$</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Hence, the uncertainty in momentum of electron i.e Δp = 5.28×10<sup>-25</sup> kg m/ sec.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 10</h3>
<div><p><p><code></code>A current of 50A is supplied in a slab of copper 0.5cm thick and 2 cm wide is placed in a magnetic field B of 1.5 T. The magnetic field is perpendicular to the plane of the slab and to the current .The free electron concentration in copper is 8.4 × 10<sup>28 </sup>electrons/m<sup>3</sup>? . What will be the magnitude of the Hall voltage across the width of the slab?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Given,</p>
<p>Current (I) = 50A</p>
<p>Thickness of copper slab (X) = 0.5cm</p>
<p>Width of copper slab (b) = 2cm</p>
<p>Magnetic field (B) = 1.5T</p>
<p>Free electron concentration (N) = 8.4×10<sup>28</sup> electrons/m3</p>
<p>Magnitude of Hall Voltage (V) = ?</p>
<p>Now,</p>
<p>We know that,</p>
<p>$$V = \frac{{IBb}}{{NqA}}$$</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">$$V = \frac{{50×1.5×2×10^{{-2}} }}{{8.4×10^{{28}}×1.6×10^{{-19}}×10^{{-4}}}}$$</p>
<p>$$V = 1.12×10^{{-6}}V$$</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">Hence, required hall voltage of the slab is 1.12×10<sup>-6 </sup>V.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 11</h3>
<div><p><p>Sodium has a body–centered cubic structure with a one–atom basis .The density and atomic weight of sodium are 0.971g/cm<sup>3</sup> and 23 g/mole. What is the length of the unit cube of the structure?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Given,</p>
<p>Density (ρ) = 0.971 g/cm<sup>3</sup></p>
<p>No. of atoms per unit cell (N) = 2</p>
<p>Atomic weight of sodium (m) = 23 g/mole</p>
<p>Length (a) = ?</p>
<p>Now,</p>
<p>We can use the formula,</p>
<p>$$\frac{{N}}{{v}} = \frac{{ρNa}}{{m}} $$   where, v is the volume.</p>
<p>$$\frac{{N}}{{a^{{3}}}} = \frac{{ρNa}}{{m}} $$</p>
<p>$$ a^{{3}} = \frac{{Nm}}{{ρNa}} $$</p>
<p>$$ a^{{3}} = \frac{{2×23}}{{0.971×6.023×10^{{23}}}} $$</p>
<p>$$ a^{{3}} = 1.573×10^{{-22}}$$</p>
<p>$$ a = 5.3×10^{{8}}cm$$</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Hence, the required length of the unit cube of the structure is 5.3×10<sup>8</sup>cm.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
